	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />I've heard global vars are bad.. but, in the context of constrained devices, isn't speed a better tradeoff than tidiness?  In my limited experience the only drawback is my own potential for errors (stepping on an already used var).
<br />
<br />I think BatariBASIC has a great way to deal with multi-bank sub-routines.  You can call "GOSUB FOO" for local routines and "GOSUB FOO BANK3" to tell the compiler it's located on another page.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>tokumaru</b> [ Fri Jan 06, 2012 6:55 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">slobu wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I've heard global vars are bad.. but, in the context of constrained devices, isn't speed a better tradeoff than tidiness?</div><br />It depends... if you have a lot of global variables you'll run out of RAM faster in systems that don't have much of it, like the NES, and that's a huge problem.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">You can call "GOSUB FOO" for local routines and "GOSUB FOO BANK3" to tell the compiler it's located on another page.</div>
<br />IMO it's not a matter of how to call them... I mean, the compiler is the one generating the ASM/binaries, so it KNOWS what routines are in different banks, it doesn't need the programmer to explicitly say it.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


